body:
@gianm I think QueryMetrics with generic methods which accept String keys and value (dimensions or metrics) doesn't add much value over what we have already.

Some dimensions/metrics are relatively expensive to compute during the query. With the type safe  "method hook" approach, dimensions/metrics which you don't need are zero-cost. With methods accepting Strings, they still have to be computed, and the logic of their computation pollutes the core query execution code. I have a specific case in mind, it's creating "bitmap construction plan" strings, presented in this message: https://github.com/druid-io/druid/pull/3754#issue-193979306. We emit such strings as dimension. It adds quite a lot of logic, and supposedly not very cheap (though I didn't measure): involves creating and populating TreeMaps, etc. I would like to completely hide this logic and complexity in our own implementation of `TopNQueryMetrics`.

If site specific QueryMetrics don't want to break on each Druid release, they may inherit from `DefaultQueryMetrics`, or `DefaultTopNQueryMetrics`, etc. Those classes act as adapter implementations as well. Elaborated that in Javadocs of QueryMetrics.

@leerho 
BTW since Druid has now officially moved to Java 8, should Memory still support Java 7? I see https://github.com/DataSketches/sketches-core/ is also Java 8.

If it shouldn't, `Memory` and `WritableMemory` could be made interfaces, because interfaces support static methods in Java 8. If you want. However should be checked that performance is the same.

Would it be too weird to have:

```
class QueryResult<T>
{
  final Sequence<T> result;
  final Future<ImmutableMap<String, Object>> responseContext;
}
```

Where `responseContext` is a future that might not be available until the `result` has finished accumulating?
